[6] Kenya - background
Date: Mon 15 Jan 2007
From: Susan Baekland <grolleyog@wanadoo.fr>

[The following information has been received from Dr Susan Baekland, a
veterinarian who formerly worked in Kenya. Her firsthand observations might
help in assessing the difficulties the authorities encounter in controlling
RVF in the affected regions. - Mod.AS]
The problem with that area, which I used to know very well indeed, is that
the Tana river has overflowed, and there have been massive rains. The
Somali and some Rendille tribesmen herd cattle, fat tailed sheep, and
goats. These animals are enclosed in a circular enclosure made of thorn
tree branches at night. They are not inside, and the herdsmen, unless they
are in one place for quite a while, will sleep in the open alongside a
fire. The Rendille make a shelter of semicircular branches covered with
hides. These residences are taken down and carried on camels when they
move. These people are going to drink the milk of their stock and probably
kill and eat a sick animal before it dies. It is a real problem.
The herds and herdsmen are scattered over huge areas looking for grazing,
often a long way off any sort of vehicular access. They can be spotted from
the air. But it all costs money, and if one is going to vaccinate
livestock, then somehow these herdsmen who are largely illiterate and very
scattered have to be informed. The only real way to contact these people is
by radio or word of mouth by a fellow tribesman, well informed and on a
camel. You can use vehicles, but they get held up all the time by the bush
and rocks, etc. But then they will suspect it is a government tax trap. It
all takes time; whether the nomads will bring their stock in for
vaccination is another matter.
--
Susan Baekland
<grolleyog@wanadoo.fr>
[The preparedness steps in Eastern Africa, particularly in the Horn of
Africa, might be of an academic nature if susceptible animals in the
RVF-prone areas remain unvaccinated. In spite of the immense difficulties
described by Susan Baekland and others, timely mass vaccinations are
crucial for the prevention of disease in animals and exposure of humans.
For description of the areas where vaccinations should be performed, see
FAO's document "Possible RVF activity in the Horn of Africa," November
2006, which includes maps; available online at
<http://www.fao.org/docs/eims/upload//217874/EW_hornafrica_nov06_rvf.pdf>.
- Mod.AS]
